Creativity is the ability to cultivate original ideas and turn them into tangible outputs. If you struggle with finding inspiration to create here’s 4 things you can try 👇

1. Nature: Simply spending time outdoors is essential and without it we feel depleted. If you’ve been in front of a computer all day go for a walk and recharge your creativity. The upside to nature is that it’s free. Plus the peace and freedom it provides has been inspiring artists for centuries. 

2. Take breaks: Resting can help you separate from a problem and approach it with a new outlook, which in my experience always leads to renewed inspiration.

3. Keep a journal: My best creative ideas usually come when I’m physically not able to act on them. So I write them down. This can be in your phone or on paper. Getting these ideas out will clear your mind while giving you a rolodex of creative sparks to tap into later.

4. Ask new questions: “What if I tried this?” “I wonder how they did that?” Attempting something outside of your comfort zone can fuel your imagination. While seeking answers to new questions will jumpstart the creative process and open the door to new possibilities.

Most photographers want to sell prints. 

- It’s just cool to see a physical version of your work. 

- It’s a nice way to make extra money as a side hustle.

After selling hundreds of prints. Here’s the pro tips I wish I knew from day 1👇

1. This may be the most important. 

The most artistic photo doesn’t always make the most desirable print. 

Think about your customer. 

What photo do they need/want on their wall?

The print below is my best seller. It’s literally a light post. 

Keep it simple.

2. Before any expensive prints create a proof print. 

I’ve wasted so much money on expensive prints that had imperfections. 

The worst being a 40x60 canvas I had to reprint because I missed a dust spot. 

Trust me the extra time invested into proofing is worth it.

3. Mount your prints if you can.

Simply put it’s way too easy for you and your customers to damage a piece of paper. 

I mount my prints because it makes them easier to ship, easier to store, and easier for the customer to preserve.

There’s multiple ways to create a photography hypelapse like this one but this is the most basic method. It’s 20% the technique and 80% creativity. I would say the creative aspect is definitely the most difficult part. Mapping out the shots and figuring out a way to make something that flows ended up being way harder than I expected. For example notice how the photos of the Atlanta Ferris wheel (a circle shape) leads into the Atl sports logos (also circle shape) and then into the Mercedes Benz stadium logo (also a circle). That was by design to try and make the flashing images move smoothly from scene to scene. Give it a try to challenge yourself as a creator and have fun with it.

Episode 8 of the Ranft book club.

Today I wanted to highlight Early Color by Saul Leiter. Every time I open this book it’s obvious how much it has influenced many of the photographs here on Instagram. If you’re looking for a different outlook on photography, and what a picture can be, I highly recommend you checkout Saul’s work. Something I couldn’t mention in this reel is that Saul hid this color photography for many years. At the time this body of work was created in New York City color photography was looked down upon. The art of photography was dominated by the black & white images and that’s what Leiter was primarily known for. It wasn’t until the 1990’s that his color work began to gain attention and become a staple of photography book collections everywhere.

I had the privilege of working with @oppo to test the camera in their new Find N3 smartphone. Swipe through and see what I came up with and let me know your favorite. I think the photos speak for themselves but this camera is so impressive. I was able to capture each image in Raw and have pro controls over the settings for each image. A good example is slide 6 where I was able to easily create a long exposure while using the folding design as a tripod. What surprised me the most was slide 5. The @oppo Find N3 has a 64 megapixel 3x zoom telephoto camera which can produce 6x zoom lossless images. This is the first time i’ve experienced this level of image quality using a mobile zoom camera. Full youtube video, with more details, is live on my channel (link in bio) and thanks @oppo for inviting me to participate in this campaign. #ad #OPPOFindN3 #FoldablesReimagined
